{{more footnotes|date=February 2012}}
'''Caesius Bassus''' was a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] lyric poet who lived in the reign of [[Nero]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Epic and Empire in Vespasianic Rome: A New Reading of Valerius Flaccus' Argonautica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z4ltLjx_2woC&pg=PA8|date=5 July 2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-964408-7|pages=8–}}</ref>

He was the intimate friend of [[Aulus Persius Flaccus|Persius]], who dedicated his sixth satire to him, and whose works he edited (''Schol. on Persius'', vi. I). He is said to have lost his life in the eruption of [[Vesuvius]] in AD 79. He had a great reputation as a poet; [[Quintilian]] (''Instit.'' x. I. 96) goes so far as to say that with the exception of [[Horace]], he was the only lyric poet worth reading.

He is also identified with the author of a treatise ''De Metris'' of which considerable fragments, probably of an abbreviated edition, are extant (ed. Keil, 1885).<ref name="HaaseTemporini1998">{{cite book|author1=Wolfgang Haase|author2=Hildegard Temporini|title=Aufstieg und Niedergang der romischen Welt: (ANRW) : Geschichte und Kultur Roms im Spiegel der neueren Forschung : Teil II : Principat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yluAyffLBScC&pg=PA3254|year=1998|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-015699-7|pages=3254–}}</ref> The work was probably originally in verse, and afterwards recast or epitomized in [[prose]] form to be used as an instruction book. An account of some of the metres of Horace (in Keil, ''Grammatici Latini'', vi. 305), bearing the title ''Ars Caesii Bassi de Metris'' is not by him but chiefly borrowed by its unknown author, from the treatise mentioned above.

