{{Infobox language |name=Caquinte |nativename=Poyenisati |states=[[Perú]] |speakers=500 |date=2012 |ref=Lyle Campbell; Verónica Grondona (27 January 2012). The Indigenous Languages of South America: A Comprehensive Guide. Walter de Gruyter. pp. 214–. {{ISBN|978-3-11-025803-5}}. |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Campa languages|Campa]] |fam4=Ashaninka |iso3=cot |glotto=caqu1242 |glottorefname=Caquinte }}
'''Caquinte''' (Caquinte Campa), also '''Poyenisati''', is an [[Arawakan language]] of [[Peru]]. It is spoken along the Poyeni, Mayapo, Picha, Yori, and Agueni rivers, with some speakers along parts of the Sensa and Vitiricaya rivers, within [[Junín, Peru]].<ref>Fabián Montoya Terrones (2002). Naciones amazónicas. Editorial San Marcos.</ref> It is an endangered language.<ref>Lyle Campbell; Verónica Grondona (27 January 2012). The Indigenous Languages of South America: A Comprehensive Guide. Walter de Gruyter. pp. 214–. {{ISBN|978-3-11-025803-5}}.</ref>
Caquinte people are a division of the [[Asháninka|Campa]] Indians. They mostly live outside the "regional [[cash economy]]". They raise [[manioc]] as protein [[Staple foods|staple]], being a [[Subsistence agriculture|subsistence agricultural]] community. Their population approximates 1000 people, with "sporadic" outside contact.<ref>James Stuart Olson (1991). The Indians of Central and South America: An Ethnohistorical Dictionary. Greenwood Publishing Group. pp. 73–. {{ISBN|978-0-313-26387-3}}.</ref>
