Notes:
# All back vowels likely had front-vowel [[allophones]] as a result of [[Germanic umlaut|Umlaut]]. The front-vowel allophones likely became full phonemes in Middle High German. In the Old High German period, there existed {{IPA|[e]}} (possibly a mid-close vowel) from the Umlaut of {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/e/}}{{clarify|date=December 2014}} but it probably wasn't phonemicized until the end of the period. Manuscripts occasionally distinguish two {{IPA|/e/}} sounds. Generally, modern grammars and dictionaries use {{angle bracket|ë}} for the mid vowel and {{angle bracket|e}} for the mid-close vowel.
# The short high and mid vowels may have been articulated lower than their long counterparts as in Modern German. This cannot be established from written sources.
# Short vowels followed later by long vowels tended to be reduced to {{angle bracket|e}} in unstressed syllables. The {{angle bracket|e}} may have represented {{IPA|[ɛ]}} or [[schwa]] {{IPA|[ə]}}.
# Vowel length was indicated in the manuscripts inconsistently (though modern handbooks are consistent). Vowel letter doubling, a [[circumflex]], or an [[acute accent]] was generally used to indicate a long vowel.{{sfn|Wright|1906|page=2}}

Old High German diphthongs are indicated by the [[digraph (orthography)|digraphs]] {{angle bracket|ei}}, {{angle bracket|ie}}, {{angle bracket|io}}, {{angle bracket|iu}}, {{angle bracket|ou}}, {{angle bracket|uo}}.

