# There is wide variation in the consonant systems of the Old High German dialects arising mainly from the differing extent to which they are affected by the [[High German Sound Shift]]. Precise information about the articulation of consonants is impossible to establish.
#In the plosive and fricative series, where there are two consonants in a cell, the first is [[Fortis (phonetics)|fortis]] the second [[lenis]]. The voicing of lenis consonants varied between dialects.
#Old High German distinguished long and short consonants. Double-consonant spellings don't indicate a preceding short vowel as in Modern German but true consonant [[gemination]]. Double consonants found in Old High German include ''pp, bb, tt, dd, ck'' (for {{IPA|/kk/}}), ''gg, ff, ss, hh, zz, mm, nn, ll, rr.''
#{{IPA|/θ/}} changes to {{IPA|/d/}} in all dialects during the 9th century. The status in the Old High German ''Tatian'' (c. 830), reflected in modern Old High German dictionaries and glossaries, is that ''th'' is found in initial position, ''d'' in other positions.
# It is not clear whether Old High German {{IPA|/x/}} had already acquired a palatalized allophone {{IPA|[ç]}} following front vowels as in Modern German.
#A [[geschwänztes Z|curly-tailed ''z'']] (''[[ȥ]]'') is sometimes used in modern grammars and dictionaries to indicate the alveolar fricative which arose from [[Common Germanic]] ''t'' in the [[High German consonant shift]], to distinguish it from the alveolar affricate, represented as ''z''. This distinction has no counterpart in the original manuscripts, except in the OHG ''Isidor'', which uses ''tz'' for the affricate.
# The original Germanic fricative ''s'' was in writing usually clearly distinguished from the younger fricative ''z'' that evolved from the High German consonant shift - the sounds of these two graphs seem not to have merged before the 13th century. Now seeing that ''s'' later came to be pronounced {{IPA|/ʃ/}} before other consonants (as in ''Stein'' {{IPA|/ʃtaɪn/}}, ''Speer'' {{IPA|/ʃpeːɐ/}}, ''Schmerz'' {{IPA|/ʃmɛrts/}} (original ''smerz'') or the southwestern pronunciation of words like ''Ast'' {{IPA|/aʃt/}}), it seems safe to assume that the actual pronunciation of Germanic ''s'' was somewhere between {{IPA|[s]}} and {{IPA|[ʃ]}}, most likely about {{IPA|[s̠]}}, in all Old High German up to late Middle High German. A word like ''swaz'', "whatever", would thus never have been {{IPA|[swas]}} but rather {{IPA|[s̠was]}}, later (13th century) {{IPA|[ʃwas]}}, {{IPA|[ʃvas]}}.


===Phonological developments===
Here are enumerated the sound changes that transformed [[West Germanic languages|Common West Germanic]] into Old High German, not including the Late OHG changes which effected [[Middle High German]] 
* {{IPA|/ɣ/}}, {{IPA|/β/}} > {{IPA|/ɡ/}}, {{IPA|/b/}} in all positions ({{IPA|/ð/}} > {{IPA|/d/}} already took place in West Germanic). Most but not all High German areas are subject to this change.
** PG *''sibi'' "sieve" > OHG ''sib'' (cf. Old English ''sife''), PG *''gestra'' "yesterday"  > OHG ''gestaron'' (cf. OE ''ġeostran'', ''ġ'' being a fricative {{IPA|/ʝ/}} )
* [[High German consonant shift]]: Inherited voiceless plosives are [[Lenition|lenited]] into fricatives and affricates, while voiced fricatives are hardened into plosives and in some cases devoiced.
** Ungeminated post-vocalic {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}}, {{IPA|/k/}} spirantize intervocalically to {{IPA|/ff/}}, {{IPA|/ȥȥ/}}, {{IPA|/xx/}} and elsewhere to {{IPA|/f/}}, {{IPA|/ȥ/}}, {{IPA|/x/}}. Cluster {{IPA|/tr/}} is exempt from this. Compare Old English ''slǣpan'' to Old High German ''slāfan''.
** Word-initially, after a resonant and when geminated, the same consonants affricatized to {{IPA|/pf/}}, {{IPA|/tȥ/}} and {{IPA|/kx/}}, OE ''tam'' : OHG ''zam''.
*** Spread of {{IPA|/k/}} > {{IPA|/kx/}} is geographically very limited and is not reflected in Modern Standard German.
** {{IPA|/b/}}, {{IPA|/d/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} are devoiced.
*** In Standard German, this applies to {{IPA|/d/}} in all positions, but to {{IPA|/b/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} only when geminated. PG *brugjo > *bruggo > ''brucca'', but *leugan > ''leggen''.
* {{IPA|/eː/}} (*''ē²'') and {{IPA|/oː/}} are diphthongized into {{IPA|/ie/}} and {{IPA|/uo/}} respectively.
* Proto-Germanic {{IPA|/ai/}} became {{IPA|/ei/}}, except before {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/h/}}, {{IPA|/w/}} and word finally, where it monophthongizes into ê ( which is also the reflex of unstressed {{IPA|/ai/}}) .
** Similarly {{IPA|/au/}} > {{IPA|/ô/}} before {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/h/}} and all dentals, otherwise {{IPA|/au/}} > {{IPA|/ou/}}. PG *''dauþaz'' "death" > OHG ''tôd'', but *''haubudą'' "head" > ''houbit''.
*** {{IPA|/h/}} refers here only to inherited {{IPA|/h/}} from PIE *k, and not to the result of the consonant shift {{IPA|/x/}}, which is sometimes written as h.
* {{IPA|/eu/}} merges with {{IPA|/iu/}} under ''i''-umlaut and ''u''-umlaut, but elsewhere is {{IPA|/io/}} (earlier {{IPA|/eo/}}). In [[Upper German]] varieties it also becomes {{IPA|/iu/}} before labials and velars.
* {{IPA|/θ/}} fortifies to {{IPA|/d/}} in all German dialects.
* Initial {{IPA|/w/}} and {{IPA|/h/}} before another consonant are dropped.

