'''Qwara''', or '''Qwareña''' (called "Falasha" (Hwarasa) in some older sources), was one of two [[Agaw languages|Agaw dialects]], spoken by a subgroup of the [[Beta Israel]] ([[Ethiopia]]n [[Jew]]s) of the [[Qwara Province|Qwara]] area. It is a dialect of [[Qimant language|Qimant]]. It is nearly extinct.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} Several early Falashan manuscripts, using the [[Ge'ez alphabet]], exist; in more recent times, the language has been recorded by several linguists and travellers, starting with Flad in 1866.

The language was on the decline in the early 20th  century, as it was being replaced by [[Amharic language|Amharic]]. During [[Operation Solomon]], most of its remaining speakers were airlifted to [[Israel]], where it continues to lose ground to [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]].

