{{Infobox person | name = Susy Delgado | image = Susy Delgado en 2011.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = Delgado in 2011. | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|12|20|df=y}} | birth_place = [[San Lorenzo (Paraguay)|San Lorenzo]], [[Paraguay]] | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | nationality = [[Paraguayan]] }} '''Susy Delgado''' (born 20 December 1949) is a [[Paraguayan]] poet and writer in Spanish and [[Guarani language|Guarani]].
==Life== Delgado was born in [[San Lorenzo (Paraguay)|San Lorenzo]] in Paraguay in 1949. After obtaining a degree in Sociology in [[Madrid]], Delgado worked as a journalist. She won international recognition in 1985 as a finalist for a Spanish poetry competition in Madrid.<ref name=anselm>{{cite web|title=Susy Delgado|url=http://www.anselm.edu/homepage/tmfaith/antologia/4_D-F.html|publisher=anselm.edu|accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref> In 2017, she won the national literature prize of Paraguay, Premio Nacional de Literatura, for her poem ''Ybytu yma''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Susy Delgado gana Premio Nacional de Literatura|url=http://www.lanacion.com.py/espectaculo_edicion_impresa/2017/10/18/susy-delgado-gana-premio-nacional-de-literatura/|website=La Nación|accessdate=6 January 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref>
Her Spanish poetry includes: ''Some lost tremor'' (1986), The ''Court of the Elves''. The latter took the Curupayty Radio Award in 1991 and the Municipal Board Award in 1992. In 2001 she had her first prose book published.<ref name=anselm/>
